{
  "doc_id": "11075",
  "text": "Executive control is the ability to flexibly control behavior on the basis of current task demands. One important aspect of executive control is the ability to rapidly inhibit or change prepared action plans, if these responses become inappropriatea function referred to as reactive control. [CITATION_1] The saccadic eye movement system is an ideal effector system for investigating the executive control of action, as the neural circuitry of saccade initiation has been well described in nonhuman primates. [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] Tasks such as the countermanding paradigm task and search-step task have been used to specifically probe reactive executive control of saccades. [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] Both tasks require rapid saccades to a target, and occasionally, the planned saccade can be inhibited or redirected upon the sudden presentation of a visual or auditory stimulus (stop or change signal).",
